<b>Andrew White Tuer</b> (1838&ndash;1900) was a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../761/68761.xml">
publisher</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../353/45353.xml">
writer</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../036/23036.xml">
printer</link>.<p>

In 1856 Tuer went to London with the plan of becoming a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../315/23315.xml">
doctor</link>.  After changing his mind he went to a merchant's office.</p>
<p>

Around 1862 Tuer set himself up as a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../676/201676.xml">
stationer</link>.  In 1863 he was joined in his venture by <link>
Abraham Field</link> and the company became <link>
Field and Tuer</link>.  The company's first book was published in 1870.  The firm became established for its illustrated books and especially for reprints of old children's books.</p>
<p>

In 1891 Field died and Tuer formed a limited company which he renamed <link>
Leadenhall Press Ltd</link>.</p>
<p>

Tuer was a keen antiquarian and was always conscious that he should document those aspects of London life that he felt were disappearing.</p>
